00:00:20.650 --> 00:00:21.830
PROFESSOR: OK, let's start.

00:00:24.530 --> 00:00:29.980
So last time, having
dealt with the ideal gas

00:00:29.980 --> 00:00:33.225
as much as possible, we started
with interacting systems.

00:00:39.420 --> 00:00:42.660
Let's say interacting gas.

00:00:42.660 --> 00:00:46.760
And the first topic
that we did was

00:00:46.760 --> 00:00:51.860
what I called an approach
towards interaction

00:00:51.860 --> 00:00:54.451
through the Cumulant expansion.

00:00:57.400 --> 00:01:03.720
The idea is that we certainly
solved the problem where

00:01:03.720 --> 00:01:14.550
we had particles in a box and
it was just a trivial system.

00:01:14.550 --> 00:01:20.690
Basically, the particles were
independent of each other

00:01:20.690 --> 00:01:23.520
in the canonical ensemble.

00:01:23.520 --> 00:01:27.540
And things become interesting
if you put interactions

00:01:27.540 --> 00:01:30.710
among all of the particles.

00:01:30.710 --> 00:01:33.480
Very soon, we will
have a specific form

00:01:33.480 --> 00:01:35.520
of this interaction.

00:01:35.520 --> 00:01:37.270
But for the beginning,
let's maintain

00:01:37.270 --> 00:01:40.190
it as general as possible.

00:01:40.190 --> 00:01:42.240
And the idea was
that we are trying

00:01:42.240 --> 00:01:46.120
to calculate the partition
function for a system that

00:01:46.120 --> 00:01:49.400
has a given temperature.

00:01:49.400 --> 00:01:54.410
The box has some volume V and
there are N particles in it.

00:01:54.410 --> 00:01:58.250
And to do so, we have
to integrate over

00:01:58.250 --> 00:02:02.140
the entirety of the phase
space of N particles.

00:02:02.140 --> 00:02:09.100
So we have to integrate over all
of the momenta and coordinates

00:02:09.100 --> 00:02:11.710
of e to the minus beta h.

00:02:11.710 --> 00:02:15.580
But we said that we are
going to first of all,

00:02:15.580 --> 00:02:18.330
note that for
identical particles,

00:02:18.330 --> 00:02:21.720
we can't tell apart
the phase space

00:02:21.720 --> 00:02:25.340
if you were to make these in
[? factorial ?] permutations.

00:02:25.340 --> 00:02:27.650
And we also made
it dimensionless

00:02:27.650 --> 00:02:30.620
by dividing by h to the 3n.

00:02:30.620 --> 00:02:33.250
And then we have e
to the minus beta

00:02:33.250 --> 00:02:39.340
h, which has a part that is
e to the minus sum over i pi

00:02:39.340 --> 00:02:43.240
squared over 2m, that
depends on the momenta.

00:02:43.240 --> 00:02:48.660
And a part that depends
on the interaction U.

00:02:48.660 --> 00:02:52.390
The integrals over the
momenta, we can easily perform.

00:02:52.390 --> 00:02:55.770
They give us the
result of Gaussians

00:02:55.770 --> 00:03:03.240
that we can express as
lambda to the power of 3n

00:03:03.240 --> 00:03:09.322
where we introduced this lambda
to be h over root 2 pi m k t.

00:03:12.770 --> 00:03:18.170
And actually, sort
of keeping in mind

00:03:18.170 --> 00:03:22.620
the result that we had for
the case of the ideal gas,

00:03:22.620 --> 00:03:28.700
let's rewrite this as V over
lambda cubed to the power of N.

00:03:28.700 --> 00:03:34.770
So I essentially divided
and multiplied by V to the N

00:03:34.770 --> 00:03:37.200
so that this part
becomes the partition

00:03:37.200 --> 00:03:42.010
function than I would
have had if U was absent.

00:03:42.010 --> 00:03:47.650
And so then the remainder is the
integral over all of the q's,

00:03:47.650 --> 00:03:50.580
but I divided by
V. So basically,

00:03:50.580 --> 00:03:53.580
with each integration,
I'm uniformly

00:03:53.580 --> 00:03:57.890
sampling all of the points
inside the box with probability

00:03:57.890 --> 00:04:02.540
density 1/V e to
the minus beta U.

00:04:02.540 --> 00:04:05.760
And we said that
this quantity we

00:04:05.760 --> 00:04:10.470
can regard as sampling
e to the minus beta U

00:04:10.470 --> 00:04:12.540
through 0 to all
other probability

00:04:12.540 --> 00:04:17.149
distribution in which the
particles ideal-like are

00:04:17.149 --> 00:04:19.160
uniformly distributed.

00:04:19.160 --> 00:04:23.870
And we call this e
to the minus beta U.

00:04:23.870 --> 00:04:27.810
And the index 0
again to indicate

00:04:27.810 --> 00:04:31.265
that we are dealing
with a uniform 0

00:04:31.265 --> 00:04:33.750
to order distribution
with respect

00:04:33.750 --> 00:04:35.584
to which this average is taken.

00:04:38.190 --> 00:04:44.060
And then, this quantity
we can write as Z0.

00:04:44.060 --> 00:04:46.760
And this exponential
we can formally

00:04:46.760 --> 00:04:51.160
express as a sum
over all, let's say,

00:04:51.160 --> 00:04:54.750
l running from 0 to
infinity minus beta

00:04:54.750 --> 00:04:58.080
to the l divided by l factorial.

00:04:58.080 --> 00:05:02.290
Then, expanding this, a quantity
that depends on the coordinates

00:05:02.290 --> 00:05:06.930
is U. So I could have U raised
to the l power, this kind

00:05:06.930 --> 00:05:10.360
of average taken
with respect to that.

00:05:10.360 --> 00:05:13.720
And immediately, my
writing something like this

00:05:13.720 --> 00:05:17.110
suggests that what
I'm after eventually

00:05:17.110 --> 00:05:20.120
is some kind of a
perturbation theory.

00:05:20.120 --> 00:05:24.460
Because I know how to solve
the problem where U is absent.

00:05:24.460 --> 00:05:26.370
That's the ideal gas problem.

00:05:26.370 --> 00:05:29.900
Maybe we can start to move
away from the ideal gas

00:05:29.900 --> 00:05:33.160
and calculate things
perturbatively

00:05:33.160 --> 00:05:34.850
in some quantity.

00:05:34.850 --> 00:05:36.910
And exactly what
that quantity is

00:05:36.910 --> 00:05:39.090
will become apparent shortly.

00:05:39.090 --> 00:05:43.260
At this time, it looks like
it's an expansion in beta U

00:05:43.260 --> 00:05:46.850
having to be a small quantity.

00:05:46.850 --> 00:05:51.050
Now, of course, for calculating
thermodynamic functions

00:05:51.050 --> 00:05:55.520
and behaviors, we don't
really rely usually on Z,

00:05:55.520 --> 00:05:59.120
but log Z, which can be
related to the free energy,

00:05:59.120 --> 00:06:01.110
for example.

00:06:01.110 --> 00:06:04.230
So taking the log
of that expression,

00:06:04.230 --> 00:06:07.490
I have a term that is log of Z0.

00:06:07.490 --> 00:06:11.190
And a term that is
the log of that sum.

00:06:11.190 --> 00:06:14.530
But we recognize that
that sum, in some sense,

00:06:14.530 --> 00:06:20.240
is a generator of moments
of this quantity U.

00:06:20.240 --> 00:06:22.020
And we have
experienced that when

00:06:22.020 --> 00:06:25.565
we take the logarithm of a
generator of moments, what

00:06:25.565 --> 00:06:29.350
we will get is a
generator of Cumulants,

00:06:29.350 --> 00:06:33.460
now starting with l
equals to 1 minus beta

00:06:33.460 --> 00:06:38.180
to the power of l
divided by l factorial U

00:06:38.180 --> 00:06:42.910
to the l0 with a subscript c.

00:06:42.910 --> 00:06:48.880
Of course, this subscript c sort
of captures all of the various

00:06:48.880 --> 00:06:51.600
subtractions that you
have to make in order

00:06:51.600 --> 00:06:54.120
to go from a moment
to a Cumulant.

00:06:54.120 --> 00:06:56.070
But that's quite
general and something

00:06:56.070 --> 00:07:00.720
that we know essentially is
relating log of the expansion

00:07:00.720 --> 00:07:02.120
to the expansion itself.

00:07:02.120 --> 00:07:03.170
But that's well-known.

00:07:05.790 --> 00:07:10.230
So presumably, I can
perturbatively calculate these.

00:07:10.230 --> 00:07:13.410
And I will have,
therefore, progressively

00:07:13.410 --> 00:07:17.130
better approximations
to log Z in the presence

00:07:17.130 --> 00:07:19.810
of this interaction.

00:07:19.810 --> 00:07:22.270
Now at this point,
we have to start

00:07:22.270 --> 00:07:29.150
thinking about a particular
expression for U.

00:07:29.150 --> 00:07:34.850
So let's imagine that our U is a
sum over pairwise interactions.

00:07:34.850 --> 00:07:37.290
So if I think about
the particles,

00:07:37.290 --> 00:07:41.030
there are molecules that
are in the gas in this room.

00:07:41.030 --> 00:07:43.880
Basically, the most important
thing is when the two of them

00:07:43.880 --> 00:07:47.960
approach each other and I have
to put a pairwise interaction

00:07:47.960 --> 00:07:50.710
between them of this form.

00:07:50.710 --> 00:07:53.280
In principle, I could add
three-point and higher-order

00:07:53.280 --> 00:07:54.530
interactions.

00:07:54.530 --> 00:07:57.290
But for all intents
and purposes,

00:07:57.290 --> 00:07:59.140
this should be enough.

00:07:59.140 --> 00:08:04.190
And then again, what I
have here to evaluate,

00:08:04.190 --> 00:08:07.735
the first term
would be minus beta,

00:08:07.735 --> 00:08:14.730
the average of the first
power, and the next one

00:08:14.730 --> 00:08:17.810
will be beta squared over 2.

00:08:17.810 --> 00:08:20.090
For the first Cumulant,
it is the same thing

00:08:20.090 --> 00:08:21.870
as the first moment.

00:08:21.870 --> 00:08:24.550
The second Cumulant is the
thing that is the variance.

00:08:24.550 --> 00:08:28.520
So this would have been
U squared 0 minus average

00:08:28.520 --> 00:08:32.633
of U squared, and then
there will be higher orders.

00:08:38.760 --> 00:08:43.669
So let's calculate these
first two moments explicitly

00:08:43.669 --> 00:08:46.250
for this potential.

00:08:46.250 --> 00:08:54.110
So the first term U in this 0
to order average, what is it?

00:08:54.110 --> 00:08:59.270
Well, that's my U. So I
have to do a sum over i

00:08:59.270 --> 00:09:06.570
and j of V of qi minus qj.

00:09:06.570 --> 00:09:08.380
What does the averaging mean?

00:09:08.380 --> 00:09:14.670
It means I have to integrate
this over all qi divided

00:09:14.670 --> 00:09:19.030
by V. Let's call this qk divided
V and this is [INAUDIBLE].

00:09:22.958 --> 00:09:28.400
OK, so let's say we look at the
first term in this series which

00:09:28.400 --> 00:09:33.390
involves V of q1 minus q2.

00:09:33.390 --> 00:09:36.800
Let's say we pick
that pair, q1 and q2.

00:09:36.800 --> 00:09:45.940
And explicitly, what I have
here is integrals over q1, q2,

00:09:45.940 --> 00:09:54.520
qn, each one of them
coming with a factor of V.

00:09:54.520 --> 00:09:58.100
Now, of course, it doesn't
matter which pair I pick.

00:09:58.100 --> 00:09:59.580
Everything is symmetric.

00:09:59.580 --> 00:10:03.090
The weight that I start
with uniformly is symmetric.

00:10:03.090 --> 00:10:06.510
So clearly, my
choice of this pair

00:10:06.510 --> 00:10:08.500
was arbitrary and
the answer when

00:10:08.500 --> 00:10:12.950
I do the sum is the answer for
1 times the number of pairs,

00:10:12.950 --> 00:10:14.680
which is N N minus 1 over 2.

00:10:19.250 --> 00:10:23.510
Now, over here I have
integrals over q3 or qn,

00:10:23.510 --> 00:10:26.260
et cetera, that don't
appear in the function

00:10:26.260 --> 00:10:27.840
that I'm integrating.

00:10:27.840 --> 00:10:32.100
So all of those integrals
will give me factors of 1.

00:10:32.100 --> 00:10:34.660
And really, the only thing
that I am going to be left with

00:10:34.660 --> 00:10:39.020
is these two integrals
over q1 and q2.

00:10:39.020 --> 00:10:42.310
But even then, the function
that I'm integrating

00:10:42.310 --> 00:10:45.230
is only a function of
the relative coordinate

00:10:45.230 --> 00:10:47.270
that I can call q.

00:10:47.270 --> 00:10:54.470
And then I can, if I want,
integrate over q1 and q.

00:10:54.470 --> 00:10:56.970
The integral over q1
would also give me

00:10:56.970 --> 00:10:59.520
1 when I divide by the volume.

00:10:59.520 --> 00:11:04.280
So the answer is going
to be N N minus 1 over 2,

00:11:04.280 --> 00:11:06.600
which is the number of pairs.

00:11:06.600 --> 00:11:11.420
The integral over the
relative coordinate times

00:11:11.420 --> 00:11:14.330
the potential-- there
is a factor of 1 over V

00:11:14.330 --> 00:11:17.780
that I can put out here.

00:11:17.780 --> 00:11:21.790
So you tell me what the
first pair potential is

00:11:21.790 --> 00:11:25.790
and I tell you that this is the
first correction that you will

00:11:25.790 --> 00:11:29.780
get once you multiply
by minus beta

00:11:29.780 --> 00:11:32.890
to log Z from which you
can calculate the partition

00:11:32.890 --> 00:11:35.450
functions.

00:11:35.450 --> 00:11:36.642
Yes.

00:11:36.642 --> 00:11:39.222
AUDIENCE: How did you turn the
product of two differentials

00:11:39.222 --> 00:11:44.670
d q1 times d q2 into
just one differential?

00:11:44.670 --> 00:11:49.590
PROFESSOR: OK, I have
the integral dq q1 dq q2,

00:11:49.590 --> 00:11:53.000
some function of q1 minus q2.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:58.160
I change variables keeping
q1 as one of my variables

00:11:58.160 --> 00:12:03.800
and q [INAUDIBLE] replace
q2 with q minus q2.

00:12:03.800 --> 00:12:06.950
So then I have the
integration over q1.

00:12:06.950 --> 00:12:10.200
I have the integration over q2.

00:12:10.200 --> 00:12:14.160
Not q2, but q f of q.

00:12:14.160 --> 00:12:15.520
And then everything's fine.

00:12:23.280 --> 00:12:25.950
All right, so that's
the first term.

00:12:25.950 --> 00:12:29.140
Let's calculate the next term.

00:12:29.140 --> 00:12:33.540
Next term becomes
somewhat interesting.

00:12:33.540 --> 00:12:39.520
I have to calculate this
quantity as a Cumulant.

00:12:39.520 --> 00:12:41.785
It's the variance.

00:12:45.900 --> 00:12:49.480
V itself is a sum over pairs.

00:12:49.480 --> 00:12:53.200
So to get V squared
to U squared,

00:12:53.200 --> 00:12:56.160
I have to essentially
square this expression.

00:12:56.160 --> 00:12:59.780
So rather than having
sum over one pair ij,

00:12:59.780 --> 00:13:02.690
I have the sum over
two pairs ij and kl.

00:13:05.890 --> 00:13:09.120
And then what I
need to calculate

00:13:09.120 --> 00:13:12.910
is an average that if
I were to square this,

00:13:12.910 --> 00:13:22.230
I will get v of qi minus
qj, v of qk minus ql 0.

00:13:22.230 --> 00:13:25.720
This will be the
average of U squared.

00:13:25.720 --> 00:13:28.900
But when I calculate
the variance,

00:13:28.900 --> 00:13:32.380
I have to subtract from it
the average of U squared.

00:13:32.380 --> 00:13:40.502
So I have to subtract V of
qi minus qj V of qk minus ql.

00:13:49.810 --> 00:13:52.510
Fine.

00:13:52.510 --> 00:13:57.190
So this is just rewriting
of that expression

00:13:57.190 --> 00:14:00.000
in terms of the sum.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:06.590
Now, each one of these is
N N minus 1 over two terms.

00:14:06.590 --> 00:14:10.016
And so this, when I sum
over all possibility,

00:14:10.016 --> 00:14:15.640
is the square of N N minus 1
over two possible terms that

00:14:15.640 --> 00:14:20.220
will occur here in the
series that I've written.

00:14:20.220 --> 00:14:26.190
Now, let's group those terms
that can occur in this as

00:14:26.190 --> 00:14:27.620
follows.

00:14:27.620 --> 00:14:33.680
One class of terms
will be when the pair

00:14:33.680 --> 00:14:45.260
ij that I pick for the first sum
is distinct from the pair kl.

00:14:45.260 --> 00:14:49.140
So huge number of terms
as I go through the pairs

00:14:49.140 --> 00:14:52.720
will have this possibility.

00:14:52.720 --> 00:14:55.400
OK, then what happens?

00:14:55.400 --> 00:15:02.640
Then when I calculate the
average of qi minus qj qk minus

00:15:02.640 --> 00:15:09.580
ql, which is this part, what
I need to do is to do all

00:15:09.580 --> 00:15:19.420
of these integral of
this form over all q's.

00:15:19.420 --> 00:15:26.630
And then I have this V of qi
minus qj V of qk minus ql.

00:15:29.745 --> 00:15:32.980
Now, my statement is that
I have, let's say here,

00:15:32.980 --> 00:15:37.450
q1 and q2 and somewhere
else q7 and q8.

00:15:37.450 --> 00:15:39.740
Or, q7 and q974.

00:15:39.740 --> 00:15:41.710
It doesn't matter.

00:15:41.710 --> 00:15:43.880
The point is that
this integral that

00:15:43.880 --> 00:15:45.810
involves this pair
of variables has

00:15:45.810 --> 00:15:47.310
nothing to do with
the integral that

00:15:47.310 --> 00:15:49.650
involves the other
pair of variables.

00:15:49.650 --> 00:15:54.460
So this answer is the same
thing as the average of qi

00:15:54.460 --> 00:16:00.120
minus qj average of qk minus ql.

00:16:00.120 --> 00:16:04.000
Essentially, in the 0 order
probability that we are using,

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:06.620
the particles are
completely independently

00:16:06.620 --> 00:16:11.040
exploring this space and these
averages will independently

00:16:11.040 --> 00:16:13.160
rely on one pair
and independently

00:16:13.160 --> 00:16:15.380
rely on another pair.

00:16:15.380 --> 00:16:21.060
And once this kind of
factorization occurs,

00:16:21.060 --> 00:16:24.640
it's clear that this
subtraction that I

00:16:24.640 --> 00:16:28.430
need to do for the variance
will get rid of this term.

00:16:28.430 --> 00:16:33.090
So these pairs do
not contribute.

00:16:33.090 --> 00:16:33.765
No contribution.

00:16:38.450 --> 00:16:41.510
If you like, this is this thing.

00:16:45.320 --> 00:16:53.678
All right, so let's do the
next possible term, ij and ik,

00:16:53.678 --> 00:16:57.710
with k not equal to this k.

00:16:57.710 --> 00:17:02.720
So basically, I make the pairs
have one point in common.

00:17:02.720 --> 00:17:05.460
So previously, I had a
pair here, a pair here.

00:17:05.460 --> 00:17:08.390
Now I joined one
of their points.

00:17:08.390 --> 00:17:11.760
So what do I get here?

00:17:11.760 --> 00:17:20.520
I will get for this average
qi minus qj qi minus ql.

00:17:20.520 --> 00:17:24.470
You can see that essentially,
the three integrals that I need

00:17:24.470 --> 00:17:27.060
to worry about are
the integrals that

00:17:27.060 --> 00:17:28.510
involve these three indices.

00:17:28.510 --> 00:17:30.810
All the others will give me 0.

00:17:30.810 --> 00:17:40.370
So this is going to be the
integral qi qj ql divided by V.

00:17:40.370 --> 00:17:47.170
I have V of qi minus
qj V of qi minus ql.

00:17:50.026 --> 00:17:52.237
AUDIENCE: You
switched [INAUDIBLE].

00:17:52.237 --> 00:17:52.820
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:17:58.720 --> 00:18:00.050
I think that's fine.

00:18:04.440 --> 00:18:06.640
All right.

00:18:06.640 --> 00:18:11.150
Now, I can do the same
thing that I did over here.

00:18:11.150 --> 00:18:13.760
I have three variables.

00:18:13.760 --> 00:18:17.370
I will pick qi to stay
as one of my variables.

00:18:17.370 --> 00:18:23.920
I replace qj with this
difference, q j i.

00:18:23.920 --> 00:18:29.440
I replace ql with
its distance to i.

00:18:32.120 --> 00:18:34.610
And again, I can
independently integrate

00:18:34.610 --> 00:18:37.810
over these three variables.

00:18:37.810 --> 00:18:41.520
So this again,
becomes the same thing

00:18:41.520 --> 00:18:50.670
as V of qi minus qj average
V of qi minus ql average.

00:18:50.670 --> 00:18:52.430
And again, there
is no contribution.

00:19:02.430 --> 00:19:06.180
Now, the first class it was
obvious because this pair

00:19:06.180 --> 00:19:09.800
and this pair were
completely distinct.

00:19:09.800 --> 00:19:12.830
This class is a
little bit more subtle

00:19:12.830 --> 00:19:17.300
because I joined one
of the points together,

00:19:17.300 --> 00:19:23.090
and then I used this and
this as well as this point

00:19:23.090 --> 00:19:25.280
as independent variables.

00:19:25.280 --> 00:19:29.450
And I saw that the sum
breaks into pieces.

00:19:29.450 --> 00:19:32.680
And you won't be
surprised if no matter

00:19:32.680 --> 00:19:37.870
how complicated I make various
more interactions over here,

00:19:37.870 --> 00:19:40.780
I can measure all of the
coordinates with respect

00:19:40.780 --> 00:19:44.150
to the single point and
same thing would happen.

00:19:44.150 --> 00:19:52.548
This class of diagrams are
called 1-particle reducible.

00:19:52.548 --> 00:19:56.160
And the first part had to
do with distinct graphs.

00:19:56.160 --> 00:19:58.090
You didn't have to
worry about them.

00:19:58.090 --> 00:20:01.170
But if I were to sort of
convert this expression--

00:20:01.170 --> 00:20:04.150
and we will do so
shortly-- into graphs,

00:20:04.150 --> 00:20:06.575
it corresponds to
graphs where there

00:20:06.575 --> 00:20:10.620
is a point from which
everything else is hanging.

00:20:10.620 --> 00:20:12.760
And measuring
coordinates with respect

00:20:12.760 --> 00:20:18.490
to that point will allow the
average to break into pieces,

00:20:18.490 --> 00:20:23.520
and then to be removed
through this subtraction.

00:20:23.520 --> 00:20:28.190
So this is simple example of
something that is more general.

00:20:28.190 --> 00:20:31.560
So at the level of this
second-order theorem,

00:20:31.560 --> 00:20:34.540
the only type of thing
that will survive

00:20:34.540 --> 00:20:40.030
is if the pairs are
identical, ij and other term

00:20:40.030 --> 00:20:41.780
is also the same pair ij.

00:20:44.380 --> 00:20:46.250
What do I get then?

00:20:46.250 --> 00:20:58.613
I get V of qi minus
qj squared minus V

00:20:58.613 --> 00:21:04.740
of qi minus qj 0 order squared.

00:21:04.740 --> 00:21:09.260
So it's the variance of a
single one of these bond

00:21:09.260 --> 00:21:11.060
contributions.

00:21:11.060 --> 00:21:14.390
If I write that in
terms of integrals,

00:21:14.390 --> 00:21:19.200
this becomes the
integral d cubed q1,

00:21:19.200 --> 00:21:26.580
d cubed q2-- well, qi qj.

00:21:26.580 --> 00:21:30.210
I will have factors
of V. Then, I

00:21:30.210 --> 00:21:39.250
would have V squared qi
minus qj for the first term

00:21:39.250 --> 00:21:51.360
and then the square of something
like this for the second term.

00:21:58.680 --> 00:22:04.560
So putting everything
together up to this order,

00:22:04.560 --> 00:22:05.580
what do I get?

00:22:05.580 --> 00:22:09.530
I will get log Z,
which is log of Z0.

00:22:09.530 --> 00:22:13.560
Let me remind you,
log of Z0 was N log

00:22:13.560 --> 00:22:24.400
of V over lambda cubed N.
That's on form such as this.

00:22:24.400 --> 00:22:26.865
And then I have
these corrections.

00:22:29.490 --> 00:22:33.520
Note that both of the
terms that have survived

00:22:33.520 --> 00:22:37.240
correspond to
looking at one pair.

00:22:37.240 --> 00:22:42.620
So the corrections will be
of the order of N N minus 1

00:22:42.620 --> 00:22:43.850
over 2.

00:22:43.850 --> 00:22:48.000
Because in both cases, I
really look at one pair.

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:55.230
The first contribution was minus
beta integral d cubed q v of q.

00:22:55.230 --> 00:22:57.600
There was a factor of
1 over V. Actually,

00:22:57.600 --> 00:23:01.270
I can take-- well, let's
put the factor of 1 over V

00:23:01.270 --> 00:23:03.970
here for the time being.

00:23:03.970 --> 00:23:10.290
The next term will be
beta squared over 2

00:23:10.290 --> 00:23:12.740
because I am looking at
the second-order term.

00:23:12.740 --> 00:23:14.701
And what do I have?

00:23:14.701 --> 00:23:19.610
I have the difference
of integral d cubed q

00:23:19.610 --> 00:23:21.240
over V V squared.

00:23:25.010 --> 00:23:32.210
And the square of the integral
of d cubed q over V V.

00:23:32.210 --> 00:23:34.910
And presumably, there
will be higher-order terms

00:23:34.910 --> 00:23:36.367
as we will discuss.

00:23:40.510 --> 00:23:45.760
Now, I'm interested in the
limit of thermodynamics

00:23:45.760 --> 00:23:47.800
where N and V are large.

00:23:51.480 --> 00:23:53.250
And in that limit,
what do I get?

00:23:53.250 --> 00:23:56.800
I will get log Z is log of Z0.

00:24:00.520 --> 00:24:10.340
And then I can see that these
terms I can write as beta.

00:24:10.340 --> 00:24:14.900
N N minus 1 I will
replace will N squared.

00:24:14.900 --> 00:24:18.250
The factors-- here I
have a 1 over V. Here,

00:24:18.250 --> 00:24:20.310
I have 1 over V squared.

00:24:20.310 --> 00:24:23.920
So this factor is
smaller by an amount that

00:24:23.920 --> 00:24:28.560
is order of V in
the large V-limit.

00:24:28.560 --> 00:24:32.770
I will bring the
factor of V outside,

00:24:32.770 --> 00:24:35.310
so I have something like this.

00:24:35.310 --> 00:24:38.090
And then, what do I have here?

00:24:38.090 --> 00:24:43.530
Actually, let's keep
this in this form,

00:24:43.530 --> 00:24:50.455
minus beta integral
d cubed q V plus beta

00:24:50.455 --> 00:24:57.460
squared over 2 integral d
cubed q V squared [INAUDIBLE].

00:25:04.590 --> 00:25:06.690
So the kinds of things
that we are interested

00:25:06.690 --> 00:25:09.980
and we can measure are
the energy of the system,

00:25:09.980 --> 00:25:11.585
but let's say we
focus on pressure.

00:25:15.700 --> 00:25:21.140
And if you look through various
things that we derived before,

00:25:21.140 --> 00:25:23.510
beta times the
pressure you can get

00:25:23.510 --> 00:25:35.220
from taking a derivative
of log Z with respect to V.

00:25:35.220 --> 00:25:39.160
We can express the log Z in
terms of the free energy,

00:25:39.160 --> 00:25:41.940
and then the derivative of free
energy with respect to volume

00:25:41.940 --> 00:25:44.830
will give you the pressure of
the various factors of beta

00:25:44.830 --> 00:25:47.660
[? and signs, ?] we
will come up with this.

00:25:47.660 --> 00:25:53.360
So from the first term, N long
V, we get our ideal gas result.

00:25:53.360 --> 00:25:57.920
Beta p is the same
thing as density.

00:25:57.920 --> 00:26:01.830
And we see that we get a
correction from here when

00:26:01.830 --> 00:26:05.420
I divide by-- when I take
a derivative with respect

00:26:05.420 --> 00:26:09.760
to V of 1 over V, I will
get minus 1 over V squared.

00:26:09.760 --> 00:26:13.040
So the next term would be
the square of the density.

00:26:16.260 --> 00:26:18.310
And then, there is
a series that we

00:26:18.310 --> 00:26:27.650
will encounter which depends
on the interaction potential.

00:26:32.960 --> 00:26:37.070
Now, it turns out that
so far I have calculated

00:26:37.070 --> 00:26:41.400
terms that relied on
only two points, ij.

00:26:41.400 --> 00:26:43.740
And hence, they
become at the end

00:26:43.740 --> 00:26:46.750
proportional to density squared.

00:26:46.750 --> 00:26:48.930
If I go further
in my expansion, I

00:26:48.930 --> 00:26:52.770
will encounter things that I
will need triangular points.

00:26:52.770 --> 00:26:56.470
For example, i j k
forming a triangle.

00:26:56.470 --> 00:26:58.490
And then, that would
give me something

00:26:58.490 --> 00:27:00.750
that would be of the order
of the density cubed.

00:27:03.300 --> 00:27:11.030
So somehow, I can also see
that ultimately this series

00:27:11.030 --> 00:27:14.080
in perturbation theory,
as we shall see,

00:27:14.080 --> 00:27:18.980
also more precisely can be
organized in powers of density.

00:27:18.980 --> 00:27:21.210
Why is that important?

00:27:21.210 --> 00:27:23.930
Because typically,
as we discussed right

00:27:23.930 --> 00:27:27.580
at the beginning, when you
look at the pressure of a gas

00:27:27.580 --> 00:27:31.050
when it is dilute and
over V is very small,

00:27:31.050 --> 00:27:34.140
it is always ideal gas-like.

00:27:34.140 --> 00:27:36.620
As you make it more
dense, you start

00:27:36.620 --> 00:27:41.300
to get corrections that you can
express in powers of density.

00:27:41.300 --> 00:27:45.020
And the coefficients of that
are called Virial coefficients.

00:27:45.020 --> 00:27:46.810
So in some sense,
we have already

00:27:46.810 --> 00:27:50.850
started in calculating the
second Virial coefficient,

00:27:50.850 --> 00:27:53.620
and there are higher-order
Virial coefficients,

00:27:53.620 --> 00:27:56.960
which together give you the
equation of states relating

00:27:56.960 --> 00:28:01.059
pressure to density
by a power series.

00:28:01.059 --> 00:28:01.850
AUDIENCE: Question.

00:28:01.850 --> 00:28:02.632
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:28:02.632 --> 00:28:04.048
AUDIENCE: The
