00:28:30.800 --> 00:28:33.886
It doesn't really matter.

00:28:33.886 --> 00:28:36.353
AUDIENCE: If the characteristic
volume of interaction

00:28:36.353 --> 00:28:37.561
is much smaller than volume--

00:28:37.561 --> 00:28:38.741
PROFESSOR: Of the space.

00:28:38.741 --> 00:28:41.032
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE], then
the integrals just converge

00:28:41.032 --> 00:28:41.660
to [? constant. ?]

00:28:41.660 --> 00:28:42.660
PROFESSOR: That's right.

00:28:42.660 --> 00:28:45.170
So if you want to be
even more precise,

00:28:45.170 --> 00:28:48.610
you will get corrections
when your particles are

00:28:48.610 --> 00:28:50.840
close to the wall and
uniformity, et cetera,

00:28:50.840 --> 00:28:52.790
is violated.

00:28:52.790 --> 00:28:55.740
So there will, actually,
be corrections to, say, log

00:28:55.740 --> 00:29:00.800
Z that are not only proportional
ultimately to number volume,

00:29:00.800 --> 00:29:03.620
but the area of the enclosure
and other [? subleading ?]

00:29:03.620 --> 00:29:04.270
factors.

00:29:04.270 --> 00:29:07.740
But in the thermodynamic
limit, we ignore all of that.

00:29:07.740 --> 00:29:11.860
So a lot of that is resolved
by this statement here.

00:29:23.240 --> 00:29:28.510
Again, you won't be surprised
that if I were to go ahead,

00:29:28.510 --> 00:29:30.740
then there will be a
term in this series that

00:29:30.740 --> 00:29:34.280
would be beta cubed over 3
factorial integral over q

00:29:34.280 --> 00:29:36.740
of vq, et cetera.

00:29:36.740 --> 00:29:43.290
And that's actually very good
because as I have written

00:29:43.290 --> 00:29:48.850
for you currently, this
