00:29:48.850 --> 00:29:50.580
Why is it useless?

00:29:50.580 --> 00:29:55.820
Because let's think back
about these two oxygen

00:29:55.820 --> 00:29:58.130
molecules in the
gas in this room

00:29:58.130 --> 00:30:01.700
and what the potential of
interaction between them

00:30:01.700 --> 00:30:04.960
would look like.

00:30:04.960 --> 00:30:08.340
Presumably, it is a function
of the relative separation.

00:30:08.340 --> 00:30:12.650
We can call it r or
q, it doesn't matter.

00:30:12.650 --> 00:30:19.260
And if you bring them
closer than the typical size

00:30:19.260 --> 00:30:24.610
of these molecules, their
potential will go to infinity.

00:30:24.610 --> 00:30:29.440
So basically, they don't want
to come close to each other.

00:30:29.440 --> 00:30:31.820
If you go very far
away, typically you

00:30:31.820 --> 00:30:33.660
have the van der
Waals attraction

00:30:33.660 --> 00:30:35.440
between the particles.

00:30:35.440 --> 00:30:37.280
So out here, it is attractive.

00:30:37.280 --> 00:30:39.820
The potential is
negative and falls off,

00:30:39.820 --> 00:30:42.980
typically, as 1 over
r to the 6 related

00:30:42.980 --> 00:30:46.360
to the polarizabilities
of the particles.

00:30:46.360 --> 00:30:51.570
And these, when you come
very short distances,

00:30:51.570 --> 00:30:54.830
the electronic
clouds will overlap

00:30:54.830 --> 00:30:57.910
and the potential
goes to infinity.

00:30:57.910 --> 00:31:02.310
And if you want to sort of think
about numbers, typical scales

00:31:02.310 --> 00:31:05.120
that we have here--
let's say here,

00:31:05.120 --> 00:31:08.730
are presumably of the
order of angstroms.

00:31:08.730 --> 00:31:11.900
And the typical depths
of these potentials

00:31:11.900 --> 00:31:16.720
in units that make sense
to statistical physics

00:31:16.720 --> 00:31:20.370
are of the order of
100 degrees Kelvin.

00:31:20.370 --> 00:31:26.370
So it's why typical
gases liquidy

00:31:26.370 --> 00:31:29.020
at range of temperatures
that is of the order of 100

00:31:29.020 --> 00:31:31.790
degrees Kelvin.

00:31:31.790 --> 00:31:37.020
Now, if I want to take this
potential and calculate this,

00:31:37.020 --> 00:31:38.920
I have trouble.

00:31:38.920 --> 00:31:44.000
Because the integral over
